{
    "title": "Fury as Trump compares impeachment inquiry to 'lynching'",
    "news": [
        {
            "id": 0,
            "text": "Donald Trump referred to impeachment proceedings against him as a \u201clynching\u201d in a Tuesday morning tweet, sparking condemnation for using such a racially charged word to describe his political predicament."
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "text": "\u201cSo some day,\u201d the president wrote, \u201cif a Democrat becomes president and the Republicans win the House, even by a tiny margin, they can impeach the president, without due process or fairness or any legal rights."
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "text": "All Republicans must remember what they are witnessing here \u2013 a lynching."
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "But we will WIN!\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "The tweet fit with Trump\u2019s history of racist remarks and his strategic use of cruelty, and some saw in it a political strategy."
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "text": "The tweet drew a chorus of outrage."
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "text": "\u201cThat is one word that no president ought to apply to himself,\u201d the South Carolina representative James Clyburn, the House majority whip, said on CNN."
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "text": "\u201cI\u2019m not just a politician \u2026 I\u2019m a product of the south."
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "text": "I know the history of that word.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "text": "The California representative Karen Bass, chairwoman of the Congressional Black Caucus, told CNN Trump\u2019s \u201clynching\u201d tweet was consistent with his pattern of throwing out \u201cracial bombs\u201d to give \u201cred meat\u201d to his base when his back is against the wall."
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "text": "Lynching is a reprehensible stain on this nation's history, as is this President."
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "text": "We'll never erase the pain and trauma of lynching, and to invoke that torture to whitewash your own corruption is disgraceful."
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "text": "\u201cYou think this impeachment is a LYNCHING?\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "text": "tweeted the Illinois representative Bobby Rush."
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "text": "\u201cWhat the hell is wrong with you?"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "text": "Do you know how many people who look like me have been lynched, since the inception of this country, by people who look like you."
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "text": "Delete this tweet.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "text": "\u201cLynching is a reprehensible stain on this nation\u2019s history, as is this president,\u201d wrote presidential candidate and California senator Kamala Harris."
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "text": "\u201cWe\u2019ll never erase the pain and trauma of lynching, and to invoke that torture to whitewash your own corruption is disgraceful.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "text": "The New Jersey senator and 2020 hopeful Cory Booker tweeted: \u201cLynching is an act of terror used to uphold white supremacy. Try again.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 21,
            "text": "Even Senate majority leader Mitch McConnell, a stalwart Trump ally, said the president had spoken poorly."
        },
        {
            "id": 22,
            "text": "\u201cGiven the history in our country I would not compare this to a lynching,\u201d McConnell told reporters on Capitol Hill."
        },
        {
            "id": 23,
            "text": "\u201cThat was an unfortunate choice of words.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 24,
            "text": "Some elected officials defended Trump."
        },
        {
            "id": 25,
            "text": "Senator Tim Scott, the sole African American Republican in Congress apart from one retiring representative, is from South Carolina."
        },
        {
            "id": 26,
            "text": "According to a report by the Equal Justice Initiative, between 1877 and 1950, 184 African Americans were lynched there."
        },
        {
            "id": 27,
            "text": "\u201cThere\u2019s no question that the impeachment process is the closest thing to a political death row trial, so I get his absolute rejection of the process,\u201d Scott said."
        },
        {
            "id": 28,
            "text": "\u201cI wouldn\u2019t use the word lynching.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 29,
            "text": "The White House claimed Trump had used the word innocently."
        },
        {
            "id": 30,
            "text": "\u201cThe president has used many words, all types of language, to talk about the way the media has treated him,\u201d said deputy press secretary Hogan Gidley."
        },
        {
            "id": 31,
            "text": "\u201cThe president wasn\u2019t trying to compare himself to the horrific history in this country at all.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 32,
            "text": "But others saw a clear and familiar political play."
        },
        {
            "id": 33,
            "text": "\u201cWhen the polls get tough, Potus turns to race,\u201d tweeted Julian Zelizer, a historian at Princeton University."
        },
        {
            "id": 34,
            "text": "\u201cLynching?!\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 35,
            "text": "tweeted the New York Time columnist Charles Blow."
        },
        {
            "id": 36,
            "text": "\u201cSir, don\u2019t you DARE invoke the darkness of America\u2019s viciousness toward black people to defend your corruption.How dare you?!\u2026\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 39,
            "text": "This is a lynching in every sense Lindsey Graham"
        },
        {
            "id": 40,
            "text": "According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), from 1882 to 1968, \u201c4,743 lynchings\u201d \u2013 that is, extrajudicial murders \u2013 \u201coccurred in the United States."
        },
        {
            "id": 41,
            "text": "Of these people that were lynched 3,446 were black.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 42,
            "text": "\u201cThese numbers seem large, but it is known that not all of the lynchings were ever recorded.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 43,
            "text": "\u201cI\u2019ve studied lynching for decades,\u201d wrote Sherrilyn Ifill, president of the NAACP legal defense and educational fund."
        },
        {
            "id": 44,
            "text": "\u201cRead hundreds of lynching accounts."
        },
        {
            "id": 45,
            "text": "Viewed almost scores of photographs."
        },
        {
            "id": 46,
            "text": "Wrote a book about lynching."
        },
        {
            "id": 47,
            "text": "Mr Trump\u2019s actions & words are consistent w/those who incited lynching, not its victims."
        },
        {
            "id": 48,
            "text": "And that fact makes this tweet particularly grotesque.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 49,
            "text": "Carol Anderson, a professor of African American studies at Emory University, confronted Trump with a tweet evoking the horrifying torture enacted on lynching victims."
        },
        {
            "id": 50,
            "text": "\u201cYou weren\u2019t castrated & forced to eat your genitalia like Claude Neal,\u201d Anderson wrote."
        },
        {
            "id": 51,
            "text": "\u201cYou weren\u2019t dragged behind a car, doused w/gasoline & set on fire like Cleo Wright. You weren\u2019t blow torched until your eyes popped out of your head like John Jones. That\u2019s lynching...\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 53,
            "text": "America\u2019s first lynching memorial and museum was opened in Montgomery, Alabama, last year."
        },
        {
            "id": 55,
            "text": "The impeachment inquiry being run by Democrats who control the House centres on Trump\u2019s attempts to get Ukraine to investigate his political rivals."
        },
        {
            "id": 56,
            "text": "Article I of the US constitution grants the House \u201cthe sole power of impeachment\u201d and Article II states that the president \u201cshall be removed from Office on Impeachment for, and Conviction of, Treason, Bribery, or other high Crimes and Misdemeanors\u201d."
        },
        {
            "id": 57,
            "text": "Lindsey Graham, the other South Carolina senator, said the process of impeachment against Trump \u201cis a lynching in every sense\u201d."
        },
        {
            "id": 58,
            "text": "Steve Vladeck, a law professor at the University of Texas, answered with \u201ca non-exhaustive list of key senses in which impeachment is not a lynching\u201d."
        },
        {
            "id": 59,
            "text": "\u201c1) It is not racially motivated."
        },
        {
            "id": 60,
            "text": "2) It is a legal process expressly set forth in the text of the constitution."
        },
        {
            "id": 62,
            "text": "3) It doesn\u2019t result in death of person being lynched.\u201d"
        }
    ],
